    englishTranslation:
      "Those who are seers of the truth have concluded that of the nonexistent (the material body) there is no endurance and of the eternal (the soul) there is no change.",
    commentary: {
      literal:
        "This is one of the most intellectually rigorous verses in the Gita, laying down the fundamental epistemology of Advaita Vedanta. Krishna defines the boundary between the Real (Sat) and the Unreal (Asat). He states: that which is 'Asat' (unreal/temporary) has no permanent existence (bhāvo). That which is 'Sat' (real/eternal) has no non-existence (abhāvo). The seers of Truth (tattva-darśibhiḥ) have observed the ultimate nature (antaḥ) of both.",
      philosophical: {
        insight: "The ultimate test for Reality: Unchanging Existence.",
        points: [
          {
            title: "The Definition of SAT (The Real)",
            text: "In Western philosophy, 'real' often means 'tangible' (you can touch it). In Vedanta, 'Real' (Sat) means 'that which exists eternally without change.' Because the physical universe, the body, and emotions are constantly changing, they fail the test of 'Sat'. Only the observing Consciousness (Ātman/Brahman) remains unchanged across past, present, and future. Therefore, only Consciousness is Real.",
          },
          {
            title: "The Definition of ASAT (The Unreal)",
            text: "Asat does not mean 'hallucination' or 'it doesn't exist.' It means it has no *independent, permanent* reality. Like a wave on the ocean: the wave is visible, but it is temporary and ultimately just water. The physical bodies Arjuna is crying over are 'Asat'—they are temporary forms that were destined to vanish the moment they were born.",
          },
        ],
      },
      psychological: {
        points: [
          {
            title: "The Root of All Anxiety",
            text: "Psychologically, 100% of human anxiety comes from confusing 'Sat' with 'Asat'. We take temporary things (our youth, our wealth, our social status, our relationships) and demand that they act like eternal things. We demand 'Sat' behavior from 'Asat' objects. The resulting friction is called suffering.",
          },
          {
            title: "Radical Acceptance",
            text: "When you truly internalize that 'of the temporary there is no endurance,' you stop fighting the flow of time. You achieve Radical Acceptance. You can enjoy the temporary world without the terror of clinging to it.",
          },
        ],
      },
      spiritual: {
        insight: "The vision of the Tattva-darśi (The Seer of Truth).",
        points: [
          {
            title: "Seeing Through the Form",
            text: "A seer of truth looks at a dying body and does not panic, because they see the 'Sat' (the eternal soul) inside the 'Asat' (the temporary body). Spiritual vision is the ability to look at the changing world and stay anchored in the unchanging observer.",
          },
        ],
      },
      scientificRational: {
        intro: "The physics of matter and empty space.",
        points: [
          {
            title: "Quantum Reality vs. Macro Illusion",
            text: "Rationally, quantum physics mirrors this verse. At the subatomic level, what we perceive as solid 'matter' (Asat) is actually 99.9999% empty space and fluctuating probability fields. It has no permanent 'solid' existence. The only constant is the underlying energy field/laws of physics (Sat) that govern the fluctuations.",
          },
        ],
      },
      modern: [
        {
          title: "Work & Career",
          text: "Your job title, your company, and the economy are 'Asat' (temporary). They will inevitably change, crash, or evolve. If you build your entire self-worth on them, you will suffer. Build your self-worth on 'Sat'—your work ethic, your integrity, your core capacity to learn. Those survive any market crash.",
        },
        {
          title: "Inner Conflicts",
          text: "When a severe depression or panic attack hits, remind yourself: 'This feeling is Asat. It had a beginning, therefore it must have an end. It has no endurance. The part of me watching the panic is Sat. It cannot be harmed.'",
        },
      ],
      mindset: {
        intro: "The shift from Delusion to Discernment:",
        points: [
          {
            title: "Identity",
            text: "Identifying with the temporary body/mind -> Identifying with the eternal observer.",
          },
          {
            title: "Thinking",
            text: "Demanding permanence from temporary things -> Accepting the flow of nature while resting in the Eternal.",
          },
          {
            title: "Action",
            text: "Desperately trying to save the 'Asat' -> Fearlessly executing duty, knowing the 'Sat' cannot be destroyed.",
          },
        ],
      },
      misinterpretations: {
        myth: [
          {
            title: "Nihilism",
            text: "Thinking that because the world is 'Asat', nothing matters and we shouldn't care about anything.",
          },
        ],
        truth: [
          {
            title: "Engaged Realism",
            text: "Vedanta is not nihilism. It does not say 'the world is garbage.' It says 'the world is temporary.' You should engage with it, love it, and fulfill your duties in it, but with the clear understanding of its nature. Do not ask a paper cup to hold boiling iron.",
          },
        ],
      },
      inquiry: [
        {
          title: "Reflective Question",
          text: "What 'Asat' (temporary thing) in my life am I currently agonizing over, treating it as if it was supposed to be 'Sat' (permanent)?",
        },
        {
          title: "Contemplative Insight",
          text: "Sorrow is the result of demanding eternity from a world of passing clouds.",
        },
      ],
    },
